untary action. For Locke, choices always involve self-consciousness. The kind of self-consciousness to which Locke appeals is intertwined with his conception of personal identity. And it is precisely this connection between the will and personal identity that reveals the special sense in which our voluntary actions can be attributed to us and the special sense in which we are active with respect to them. Deftly written and tightly focused, Liberty Worth the Name will find readers far beyond Locke studies and early modern British philosophy, including scholars interested in free will, action theory, and ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFree will and determinism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aBramhall, Bishop.  aHobbeseanism.  aaddiction.  aattributability.  aawareness.  acausal chains, deviant.  acausal explanation.  acausal overdetermination.  achangeling.  acompatibilism.  acompulsion.  acorpuscularianism.  adeliberation.  adeterminism, causal.  aeducation.  aegoism.  aevaluation.  aevaluative facts.  afreedom of action.  agood.  ahabituation.  ahappiness.  aimagination.  aindoctrination.  aintention.  ajudgment.  alanguage.  amathematics.  amechanism.  amodification.  amotivation.  anatural law.  anaturalism.  anecessity.  anegligence.  anotions.  aopenness.  aparalysis.  apassion.  apersonal identity.  apleasure.  arationality.  areflection.  arevelation.  asacrifice.  aself-consciousness.  asubstance.  asuspension.  atemptation.  atheology.  atime pressures.  auneasiness.  avoluntariness.  avoluntarism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinc